%N A396510 a(n) is the maximum integer k such that rad(k)=rad(k+2n), where rad(x) is the squarefree kernel of x (A007947).
%C A396510 Note that the equation rad(k)=rad(k+n) has no solutions for odd n. Thus, parameterizing the difference as 2n is the natural formulation.
%C A396510 Since rad(k)=rad(k+2n), the prime factors of k and k+2n must divide 2n. Thus, finding k reduces to solving the S-unit equation y-x=2n over the primes dividing 2n. Mahler's theorem guarantees a finite number of solutions, hence a maximum k exists. Terms were rigorously computed using unconditional bounds from Baker's theory of linear forms in logarithms.
%H A396510 Banri Ogawa, <a href="/A396510/b396510.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A396510 Banri Ogawa, <a href="/A396510/a396510.txt">SageMath program</a>
%e A396510 For n=77, rad(k)=rad(k+154). The maximum k satisfying this is a(77)=2662 (rad(2662)=rad(2662+154)=22).
%o A396510 (SageMath) # See Links.
%Y A396510 Cf. A396513 (minimum k).
